<h1>Terms of Service</h1>

<p class="lead">
  These terms cover your use of Remindly. The most important part is the one just
  below: Remindly helps, but it is not a medical device and must not be the only
  thing standing between someone and a missed dose.
</p>

<p><em>Last updated: July 24, 2026.</em></p>

<div class="note">
  <p>
    <strong>Remindly is a reminder tool, not medical care.</strong> It is not a
    medical device and does not give medical advice. Reminders can be delayed or
    missed — the reminder screen has to stay open, sound will not play until
    someone taps the screen, and delivery depends on the device, its browser, and
    the network. Please do not rely on Remindly as the only safeguard for
    medication, health, or safety. It is a help, not a guarantee.
    <strong>In an emergency, call your local emergency number.</strong>
  </p>
</div>

<h2>Who provides Remindly</h2>
<p>
  Remindly is provided by Anakhsoft ("we", "us"). By using Remindly you agree to
  these terms. If you do not agree, please do not use the service. Questions:
  <a href="mailto:hello@remindly.care">hello@remindly.care</a>.
</p>

<h2>Your account</h2>
<p>
  Remindly has no passwords — you sign in with a one-time link sent to your email,
  so keep your email account secure. An account is for one person; you are
  responsible for what happens under yours. You must be an adult to use Remindly.
</p>

<h2>Caregivers and the people they care for</h2>
<p>
  Remindly is built for caregivers to set up reminders for a senior, which means a
  caregiver can see that person's reminders and care history. Only set Remindly up
  for someone who has agreed to it. A caregiver can remove themselves from a senior
  at any time, and either person can ask us to end a link by emailing
  <a href="mailto:hello@remindly.care">hello@remindly.care</a>. You agree to use
  another person's information only to help care for them.
</p>

